<TITLE> US envoy discusses energy ties with Turkmenistan </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 ASHGABAT, Feb 28 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - A senior US official discussed energy cooperation with Turkmenistan's president on Thursday as part of Washington's push to cement closer ties with the gas-producing Caspian nation. Foreign delegations have flocked to Turkmenistan since President Kurbanguly Berdymukhamedov, seen as a reformist, came to power following the 2006 death of absolutist leader Saparmurat Niyazov. On Thursday, a delegation led by US Deputy Assistant Secretary of State Steven Mann arrived in the capital Ashgabat for talks with the new leader and to explore opportunities. "Ambassador Mann has met President Kurbanguly Berdymukhamedov and other government officials to discuss issues of energy and bilateral relations," the US embassy in Ashgabat said in a statement. Isolated under Soviet rule and then Niyazov's two-decade reign, the desert nation is trying to open up, diversify its energy ties and attract more foreign investment. Turkmenistan exports most of its natural gas through Russia, but the West is lobbying for an alternative route. The United States has particularly backed the Nabucco pipeline, designed to help Europe diversify gas imports away from Russia, but the long-delayed project is facing growing competition from a rival Russian project, South Stre
